   "source": [
    "# The Greeks\n",
    "\n",
    "The Greeks are measures of sensitivity of an option to changes in different parameters. Each measurement can be taken from a partial derivative of the Black-Scholes formula. There are mainly five:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Delta ($\\Delta$) - measures the sensitivity of an option's price to changes in the price of the underlying asset.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Delta = \\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial S}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- Gamma ($\\Gamma$) - measures the rate of change between an option's delta and the underlying asset's price.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Gamma = \\frac{\\partial \\Delta}{\\partial S} = \\frac{\\partial^2 V}{\\partial S^2}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- Theta ($\\Theta$) - measures the rate of change of an option's price as time passes, also known as \"time decay\".\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Theta = \\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial t}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- Vega ($\\nu$) - measures the sensitivity of an option's price to changes in the volatility of the underlying asset.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\nu = \\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial \\sigma}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- Rho ($\\rho$) -  measure the sensitivity of an option's price to changes in the risk-free interest rate.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\rho = \\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial r}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "## Delta\n",
    "\n",
    "The Delta measures the first-order sensitivity of an option's price to a change in the underlying asset's price. To obtain the formula for the Delta of an option, we can calculate the partial derivative of the Black-Scholes formula toa change in the underlying asset's price:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Delta = \\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial S}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial S} & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (S\\Phi(d_1) - e^{-r(T-t)}K\\Phi (d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (S\\Phi(d_1)) - \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (e^{-r(T-t)}K\\Phi (d_2))\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's start by calculating the partial derivative of the first component. We can use the product rule:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (S\\Phi(d_1)) & = \\Phi(d_1) \\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial S}  + S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi(d_1) + S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, we calculate the second component:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (e^{-r(T-t)}K\\Phi (d_2)) & =  e^{-r(T-t)}K \\frac{\\partial \\Phi (d_2)}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = e^{-r(T-t)}K \\frac{\\partial \\Phi (d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial S}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "To solve the partial derivative, we apply the chain rule:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "e^{-r(T-t)}K \\frac{\\partial \\Phi (d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial S} & = e^{-r(T-t)}K \\Phi'(d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}) \\frac{\\partial (d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = e^{-r(T-t)}K \\Phi'(d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}) \\frac{\\partial (d_1)}{\\partial S}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The CDF of a standard normal distribution is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Phi(d) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} \\int_{-\\infty}^{d} e^{-x^2/2}dx$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Which means that, by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, its derivative is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Phi'(d) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-d^2/2}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is also the formula for the PDF, which makes sense, since the cumulative of the probability is equal to calculating the integral of the function from negative infinite.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given the derivative of the CDF, and the formula for the parameter $d_1$, we have:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\Phi'(d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}) & = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{1}{2}(d_1-\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})^2} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{1}{2}(d_1^2 - 2 d_1 \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t} + \\sigma^2(T-t))} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{d_1^2}{2} + d_1 \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t} -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = (\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{d_1^2}{2}}) e^ {d_1 \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t} -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) e^ {d_1 \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t} -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) e^ {\\frac{log(\\frac{S}{K}) + (r + \\sigma^2/2)(T-t)}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t} -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) e^ {log(\\frac{S}{K}) + (r + \\sigma^2/2)(T-t) -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) e^ {log(\\frac{S}{K}) + r(T-t) + \\frac{\\sigma^2 (T-t)}{2} -\\frac{\\sigma^2(T-t)}{2}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) e^ {log(\\frac{S}{K}) + r(T-t)} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{S}{K} e^ {r(T-t)}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Which means that the second component is equal to:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "e^{-r(T-t)}K \\Phi'(d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}) \\frac{\\partial (d_1)}{\\partial S} & = e^{-r(T-t)}K \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{S}{K} e^ {r(T-t)} \\frac{\\partial (d_1)}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{\\partial (d_1)}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi (d_1)}{\\partial S}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Back to the derivative of the Black-Scholes formula:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial S} & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (S\\Phi(d_1)) - \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} (e^{-r(T-t)}K\\Phi (d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi(d_1) + S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S} - S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi (d_1)}{\\partial S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\Phi(d_1)\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The formula for the Delta ($\\Delta$) of a European-style call option that pays no dividend is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Delta_c = \\Phi(d_1)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can do the same process for put options, which would yield the formula:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Delta_p = \\Phi(d_1) -1 $$\n",
    "\n",
    "The Delta for a call option has a range between 0 and 1, indicating the percentage change in the option price relative to a change in the underlying asset price. While, the Delta for a put option ranges from -1 to 0.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Delta As a Proxy\n",
    "\n",
    "The Delta is also seen as a proxy for the probability of an option expiring in-the-money. One way we can interpret the Black-Scholes formula for a call option is as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$C = S\\Phi(d_1) - e^{-r(T-t)}K\\Phi (d_2)  = (what\\ we\\ expect\\ to\\ receive) - (what\\ we\\ expect\\ to\\ pay)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that the second component is what we expect to pay. If the $e^{-r(T-t)}K$ represents the present value of strike price, the $\\Phi(d_2)$ represents the probability of paying this amount or the probability of exercising this option. When we exercise the option, or when $S_T > K$, we say that the option expires in-the-money. \n",
    "\n",
    "The $\\Phi(d_2)$ probability is not exactly equal to Delta ($\\Phi(d_1)$). However, depending on the value of $\\sigma$ and $T$, it is close enough to be used as a proxy.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Delta Hedging\n",
    "\n",
    "The Delta is also used for Delta hedging or creating a Delta-neutral portfolio. A Delta-neutral portfolio is one where the sum of all Deltas is zero. This means that its value won't change if the stock price makes a small move up or down.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's take for example a portfolio where we sell 1 call option contract, representing 100 shares. We're selling a contract that gives the buyer the right but not the obligation of buying 100 stocks by a certain strike price. Let's also assume that the shorted call option has a Delta of 0.60.\n",
    "\n",
    "Since we're shorting the call option, our Delta would be negative as $-0.60 \\times 100\\ shares = -60$. So, if the stock price rises by \\$1, the option's price will increase by \\$0.60 per share and we lose \\$60.\n",
    "\n",
    "To neutralize the -60 Delta, we have to make a position with +60 Delta. The underlying stock has a Delta of 1. Therefore, we can just buy 60 shares of the underlying stock to neutralize the negative Delta position, resulting in a Delta-neutral portfolio.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Gamma\n",
    "\n",
    "The Gamma measures the rate of change between the option's Delta and the underlying asset's price. In other words, the Gamma is the second-order partial derivative of the option's value:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Gamma = \\frac{\\partial^2 C(S, t)}{\\partial S^2} = \\frac{\\partial \\Delta}{\\partial S} = \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Again, we can apply the chain rule:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S} = \\Phi' (d_1) \\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial S}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Calculating the partial derivative of $d_1$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial S} & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} \\frac{log\\frac{K}{S} + (T-t)(r + \\frac{\\sigma^2}{2})}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} \\frac{log(S)-log(K) + (T-t)(r + \\frac{\\sigma^2}{2})}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} \\frac{log(S)}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial S} log(S) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \\frac{1}{S} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{1}{S \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} \n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Which means that:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial S} = \\frac{\\Phi' (d_1)}{S \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}} = \\frac{e^{-d_1^2/2}}{S\\sigma\\sqrt{2\\pi(T-t)}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the formula for the Gamma of an European-style option with no dividends is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Gamma = \\frac{\\Phi' (d_1)}{S \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "When we calculate the second-order partial derivative of the Black-Scholes formula for a put option, we find the same results, which means that the formula above is valid for both call and put options.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Dynamic Hedging\n",
    "\n",
    "As we've seen in the last topic, the Delta can be used to create Delta-neutral portfolios. However, the Delta is not constant over time, it can change as the underlying asset's price moves. Since the Gamma measures the rate of change in Delta, we can use it to calculate how many shares we should buy or sell to maintain a Delta-neutral position.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's continue with the example from the topic on Delta Hedging. The current portfolio has a Delta of 0, since we shorted the call option and bought 60 shares of the underlying stock. Assuming a Gamma of 0.40, means that an increase of \\$1 in the underlying stock price increases the Delta by 0.04. Therefore, the new Delta will be $0.60+0.04=0.64$ per share, and the new Delta for the portfolio will be $-0.64\\times 100 = -64$. In order to neutralize the Delta, we should buy 4 shares of the underlying stock.\n",
    "\n",
    "This constant rebalancing to maintain a Delta-neutral portfolio is called Dynamic Hedging.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Theta\n",
    "\n",
    "The Theta measures the rate of change of an option's price due to the passing of time. For that reason, the Theta is also commonly called the decay in price of an option.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\Theta & = \\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial t} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} (S\\Phi(d_1)-Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} S\\Phi(d_1)-\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The first component can be easily obtained as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} S\\Phi(d_1) = S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial t} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "We could calculate the partial derivative of the CDF, but it will later get canceled out, so we can leave it as it is for now.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, the second component needs a little of work:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) & = K \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial t} e^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)\\\\\n",
    "  & = K (\\Phi(d_2) \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial t} e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial t} \\Phi(d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K (\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) \\frac{\\partial d_2}{\\partial t} ) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K (\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) \\frac{\\partial (d_1 - \\sigma\\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial t} ) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K (\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}-\\frac{\\partial \\sigma\\sqrt{T-t}}{\\partial t}) ) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K (\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}+\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}) ) \\\\\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We have seen previously that $\\Phi'(d_2)=\\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{S}{K}e^{r(T-t)}$, meaning that:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) & = K (\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{S}{K}e^{r(T-t)} (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}+\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}})) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} + K e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{S}{K}e^{r(T-t)} (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}+\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} +  S\\Phi'(d_1) (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}+\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} +  S\\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial t}+S\\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}} \\\\\n",
    "  & = K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} +  S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial t}+S\\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Going back to the original equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\Theta & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} S\\Phi(d_1)-\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) \\\\\n",
    "  & = S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial t} - K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} -  S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial t}-S\\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}\\\\\n",
    "  & = - K\\Phi(d_2) r e^{-r(T-t)} -S\\Phi'(d_1)\\frac{\\sigma}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the formula for the Vega of an European-style option that pays no dividends is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Theta_c = - rK\\Phi(d_2) e^{-r(T-t)} - \\frac{\\sigma S\\Phi'(d_1)}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Notice that the value will be negative, meaning that the value will lose value as time goes by. That is why the Theta is also called decay.\n",
    "\n",
    "When we calculate the partial derivative of the Black-Scholes formula for a put option, we get:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Theta_p = rK\\Phi(-d_2) e^{-r(T-t)} - \\frac{\\sigma S\\Phi'(d_1)}{2\\sqrt{T-t}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "As time nears the maturity date, options decay faster, so the Theta increases. Long calls and puts usually have a negative Theta, while short ones have positive Theta. A stock has zero Theta, because it's not eroded by time. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Profiting from Theta Decay\n",
    "\n",
    "Again, we return to the Delta hedging portfolio. As time passes, the option you sold becomes cheaper due to Theta decay. If the stock price and volatility stay relatively stable, you can eventually buy back the same option for a lower price, and pocket the difference.\n",
    "\n",
    "So, suppose the call option was sold by \\$200. The Delta hedge ensures that even if the stock price moves up or down, our gains or loses from the stock position will offset the gains or loses from our short option position. After the option is eroded with time, we could buy back the same option position for a lower price, say \\$50. At the end, we would've made a profit of \\$150.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Vega\n",
    "\n",
    "The Vega measures the sensitivity of a option's price to changes in the volatility of the underlying asset's price. We will calculate it like the previous Greeks, as the partial derivative of the Black-Scholes formula:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\nu & = \\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial \\sigma} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} (S\\Phi(d_1)-Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} S\\Phi(d_1)-\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Again, the first component will be just:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} S\\Phi(d_1) = S \\frac{\\partial\\Phi(d_1)} {\\partial \\sigma}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, for the second component:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) & = Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_2)}{\\partial \\sigma}  \\\\\n",
    "  & = Ke^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) \\frac{\\partial d_2}{\\partial \\sigma} \\\\\n",
    "  & = Ke^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{S}{K} e^ {r(T-t)} \\frac{\\partial (d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial \\sigma} \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\Phi'(d_1) (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial \\sigma} - \\frac{\\partial (\\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})}{\\partial \\sigma}) \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\Phi'(d_1) (\\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial \\sigma} - \\sqrt{T-t}) \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial \\sigma} - S \\Phi'(d_1) \\sqrt{T-t} \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\frac{\\partial\\Phi(d_1)} {\\partial \\sigma} - S \\Phi'(d_1) \\sqrt{T-t}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Back to the first equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\nu & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} S\\Phi(d_1)-\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\sigma} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) \\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\frac{\\partial\\Phi(d_1)} {\\partial \\sigma} - S \\frac{\\partial\\Phi(d_1)} {\\partial \\sigma} + S \\Phi'(d_1) \\sqrt{T-t}\\\\\n",
    "  & = S \\Phi'(d_1) \\sqrt{T-t}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the Vega for an European-style option with no dividends is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\nu = S \\Phi'(d_1) \\sqrt{T-t}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The $\\sqrt{T-t}$ component means that an option's Vega decays over time, approaching zero as the maturity date gets closer. The reason for that is the time for volatility to have an impact decreases when time passes. The Vega for long-dated options is higher than short-dated ones.\n",
    "\n",
    "If we do the same calculations for the put option, we would find the same results. So, the formula for the Vega is the same for both call and put options.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Profiting from Vega\n",
    "\n",
    "Options become more valuable as volatility increases. Options provide the potential of unlimited profit but a strictly limited loss. So, as volatility increases, a huge upward swing could lead to massive profits. While, a huge downward swing wouldn't make much difference, since the loss is capped.\n",
    "\n",
    "One trading strategy would be to buy options with high Vega when we expect the volatility to increase. The opposite is also viable, shorting options with high Vega when we expect the volatility to decrease.\n",
    "\n",
    "After buying the options, we could Delta hedge it, removing the risk of losing money with price swings.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Rho\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, we have the Rho, which measures the sensitivity of an option's price to changes in the risk-free interest rate.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\rho & = \\frac{\\partial C(S, t)}{\\partial r} \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} (S\\Phi(d_1)-Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)) \\\\\n",
    "  & = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} S\\Phi(d_1)-\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "One last time, the first component can be calculate as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} S\\Phi(d_1) = S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial r} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can work the second component as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} Ke^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2) & = K\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} e^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)\\\\\n",
    "  & = K(\\Phi(d_2)\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} e^{-r(T-t)}+e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_2) \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_2)}{\\partial r})\\\\\n",
    "  & = K(-\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t) + e^{-r(T-t)} \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{S}{K} e^ {r(T-t)} \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r} (d_1 - \\sigma \\sqrt{T-t})) \\\\\n",
    "  & = K(-\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t) + \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{S}{K} \\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial r}) \\\\\n",
    "  & = -K\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t) + S \\Phi'(d_1) \\frac{\\partial d_1}{\\partial r} \\\\\n",
    "  & = -K\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t) + S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial r}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Back to the initial equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\rho & = S\\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial r} + K\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t) - S \\frac{\\partial \\Phi(d_1)}{\\partial r} \\\\\n",
    "  & = K\\Phi(d_2)e^{-r(T-t)}(T-t)\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the Rho for an European-style option with no dividends is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\rho_c = K(T-t)e^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(d_2)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Whereas, for a put option we have:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\rho_p = -K(T-t)e^{-r(T-t)}\\Phi(-d_2)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Looking at the formulas, we see that call options have a positive Rho, this means that a higher interest rate increases the value of the call option. An increase in interest rates result in the increase of the opportunity cost of holding cash to buy the stock, making the right to buy later more valuable. \n",
    "\n",
    "For example, let's suppose with have \\$10,000 and interest rates are high. Instead of spending that amount of money buying stocks, we could spend less in an option premium, say \\$500, and let the remaining \\$9,500 sit in an account earning interest. Then, later we could exercise the call option if we want in the future.\n",
    "\n",
    "Conversely, put options have negative Rho because higher rates decrease the present value of the cash we would receive from selling the stock, making the put less valuable."
