    "## Greeks in Python\n",
    "\n",
    "With the formulas above, we can write some Python functions to calculate the Greeks. Let's define a class called `Option`, that takes 6 parameters when initialized: sigma (underlying asset's volatility), K (strike price), S (underlying asset's current price), T (time to maturity), r (risk-free interest rate) and the option_type, whether it's a call or put option. Within this class, we'll also define some functions:\n",
    "\n",
    "- `_calculate_d1_d2` - returns the parameters $d_1$ and $d_2$.\n",
    "- `price` - returns the price of the option using the Black-Scholes formula.\n",
    "- `delta` - returns the Greek Delta (option's sensitivity to S).\n",
    "- `gamma` - returns the Greek Gamma (delta's sensitivity to S).\n",
    "- `theta` - returns the Greek Theta (option's sensitivity to time).\n",
    "- `vega` - returns the Greek Vega (option's sensitivity to sigma).\n",
    "- `rho` - returns the Greek Rho (option's sensitivity to the risk-free interest rate).\n",
    "\n",
    "For the CDF, we'll use the `scipy.stats` library. Additionally, the derivative of the CDF is the PDF, so we'll also use the `scipy.stats` for the PDF."
   ]
